  "body": "# ðŸš€ Feature Request\r\n\r\n### Description\r\n\r\nCurrently, a `Service` struct in the Prysm codebase, such as the blockchain service, initial sync service, rpc service, etc. all have a massive number of struct fields. These services also have a `Config` struct that allows us to initialize them, leading to a ton of duplicated code. For example:\r\n\r\n```go\r\ntype Config struct {\r\n  GenesisTime time.Time\r\n  Database db.Database\r\n  NetworkID string\r\n  ...\r\n  IndexedAttestationsFeed *event.Feed\r\n}\r\n\r\ntype Service struct {\r\n  genesisTime time.Time\r\n  database db.Database\r\n  networkID string\r\n  ...\r\n  indexedAttestationsFeed *event.Feed\r\n}\r\n\r\nfunc New(ctx context.Context, cfg *Config) *Service {\r\n  return &Service{\r\n    genesisTime: cfg.GenesisTime\r\n    database: cfg.Database,\r\n    networkID: cfg.NetworkID,\r\n    ...\r\n    indexedAttestationsFeed: cfg.IndexedAttestationsFeed\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis means we have to write the code essentially 3 times! Some services have over 30 struct fields, making this incredibly hard to deal with and diffs impossible to read when adding new fields.\r\n\r\n### Describe the solution you'd like\r\n\r\nThe optimized slasher refactor #8331, introduced a new pattern which we should use across all of Prysm:\r\n\r\n```go\r\ntype Config struct {\r\n  GenesisTime time.Time\r\n  Database db.Database\r\n  NetworkID string\r\n  ...\r\n  IndexedAttestationsFeed *event.Feed\r\n}\r\n\r\ntype Service struct {\r\n  cfg *Config\r\n  // Add other unexported, service-specific fields below:\r\n  ...\r\n}\r\n\r\nfunc New(ctx context.Context, cfg *Config) *Service {\r\n  return &Service{\r\n    cfg: cfg,\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n",
